First, we analyze the given condition for small values of \( n \): - For \( n = 1 \): \( 7x_0 \equiv 1 \pmod{2} \) implies \( x_0 = 1 \). - For \( n = 2 \): \( 7(1 + 2x_1) \equiv 1 \pmod{4} \) implies \( x_1 = 1 \). - For \( n = 3 \): \( 7(1 + 2 + 4x_2) \equiv 1 \pmod{8} \) implies \( x_2 = 1 \). - For \( n = 4 \): \( 7(1 + 2 + 4) \equiv 1 \pmod{16} \) implies \( x_3 = 0 \). - For \( n = 5 \): \( 7(1 + 2 + 4 + 8x_4) \equiv 1 \pmod{32} \) implies \( x_4 = 1 \). - For \( n = 6 \): \( 7(1 + 2 + 4 + 8 + 16x_5) \equiv 1 \pmod{64} \) implies \( x_5 = 1 \). Continuing this process, we observe a pattern starting from \( n = 3 \). The bits \( x_3, x_4, x_5, \ldots \) follow a repeating cycle of 0, 1, 1. Specifically, from \( n = 3 \) onwards, every three bits are 0, 1, 1. To determine \( x_{2019}, x_{2020}, x_{2021}, x_{2022} \): - \( x_{2019} \): Calculate \( (2019 - 3) \mod 3 = 2016 \mod 3 = 0 \), corresponding to the first element in the cycle (0). - \( x_{2020} \): Calculate \( (2020 - 3) \mod 3 = 2017 \mod 3 = 1 \), corresponding to the second element in the cycle (1). - \( x_{2021} \): Calculate \( (2021 - 3) \mod 3 = 2018 \mod 3 = 2 \), corresponding to the third element in the cycle (1). - \( x_{2022} \): Calculate \( (2022 - 3) \mod 3 = 2019 \mod 3 = 0 \), corresponding to the first element in the cycle (0).
